Hey, 

your IDE should be smart enough to resolve the Macros. I actually had your behaviour the default for Glad 2 for a bit until I realized that this unfortunately breaks code, you no longer can take the address of the function pointer.

```c
#include <iostream>
#include <string>


void test(int i) {
    std::cout << "Test -> " << i << "\n";    
}

#define foo test
#define bar(i) bar(i)

int main()
{
  (*(&test))(3);
  (*(&foo))(5);
  (*(&bar))(7); // < Error
}
```

And I think there were a few more problems with it .. I just can't think of them right now.

If that works for you it is great, I am just not sure if it makes sense to include it since it will break when you least need it.

So I am not sure if including such an option would make sense. If you still wanna make the Pull Request (can't promise anything), you should do it for the glad2 branch, since I am will not work on new features for glad1 (master). Note: the generator for glad2 is completely different and uses a proper template engine now, so the code you wrote for glad1 (master) won't be easily portable (but overall it should be way easier to include).

