If you don't do `pipenv install -e .`, then the dependencies of your app (from setup.py) don't get added to `Pipfile.lock` (unless you copy them from `setup.py` to `Pipfile`, which you can do, but then you have to remember to keep all that in sync)

@techalchemy: I don't think resolving dependencies is what takes the bulk of installation time. Some projects will have a lot of dependencies, some of which will take a long time to download, some of which will be compiled from source, and having to re-install the same dependencies on every Docker build is inefficient (and unnecessary).

Yes it seems that the current best option is to copy dependencies from `setup.py` to `Pipfile` (and remember to always keep them in sync), not put `-e .` in there, and do `pipenv install --deploy` then `pip install -e .`

