@dbinetti My instructions were written with Python 2 in mind. In Python 2, the default string type is `str` which is actually an array of bytes. In Python 3, the default string type is `str` which is equivalent to the `unicode` type in Python 2. You can retrieve the bytes instead of unicode from a file in Python 3 by using `open('filename', 'rb')` or by calling the `.encode()` method on the string.

When using `cryptography`, you should take care to understand which version of Python you are using since `cryptography` prefers to work with raw bytes (string in Python 2 or bytes in Python 3). 

The instructions in the FAQ are correct but I could see that it might be helpful to include something explaining they are written with Python 2 in mind.

